<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="75" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="75">General distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raf., New Fl. [Rafinesque] 4: 16" authorityYear="1836" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Sesuvium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sesuvium verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">Sesuvium verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in North Mexico and the southern part of the USA (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferren, WR" journalOrPublisher="4. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford" pageId="33" pageNumber="78" pagination="80 - 81" refId="B20" refString="Ferren, WR, 2003. Sesuvium. In: Flora of North America, North of Mexico, Vol. 4. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford: 80 - 81" title="Sesuvium." volumeTitle="Flora of North America, North of Mexico, Vol." year="2003">Ferren 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Outside of its native range in the New World, it is reported as an introduced species in South-West Asia: Bahrain (
<bibRefCitation author="Verdcourt, B" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="37" pageNumber="82" refId="B84" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1985. An introduced Sesuvium (Aizoaceae) in Arabia. Kew Bulletin 40(1): 208." title="An introduced Sesuvium (Aizoaceae) in Arabia. Kew Bulletin 40 (1): 208." year="1985">Verdcourt 1985</bibRefCitation>
; see also specimens at BM! E! and K!), the eastern part of Saudi Arabia (
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, AG" editor="Miller, AG" journalOrPublisher="l. University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="35" pageNumber="80" pagination="155 - 168" refId="B57" refString="Miller, AG, 1996. Aizoaceae. In: Miller, AG, Cope, TA, Eds., Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol. l. University Press, Edinburgh: 155 - 168" title="Aizoaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol." year="1996">Miller 1996</bibRefCitation>
; specimens at E!, K!), Iran (
<bibRefCitation author="Fadaie, F" journalOrPublisher="Iranian Journal of Botany" pageId="33" pageNumber="78" pagination="87 - 88" refId="B19" refString="Fadaie, F, Attar, F, Ghahreman, A, 2006. A new record of Aizoaceae (Sesuvium verrucosum Raf.) for the flora of Iran. Iranian Journal of Botany 12 (1): 87 - 88" title="A new record of Aizoaceae (Sesuvium verrucosum Raf.) for the flora of Iran." volume="12" year="2006">Fadaie et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
) and United Arab Emirates (collections from Sharjah, 2009, K!). As indicated on the sheets from Bahrain (collected by M. Cornes and A.M. Alder, 1983-1985, E!), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread species in irrigated areas and loamy sands. In Saudi Arabia, it is invasive in diverse inland plant communities including wastelands and salt pans (
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, AG" editor="Miller, AG" journalOrPublisher="l. University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="35" pageNumber="80" pagination="155 - 168" refId="B57" refString="Miller, AG, 1996. Aizoaceae. In: Miller, AG, Cope, TA, Eds., Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol. l. University Press, Edinburgh: 155 - 168" title="Aizoaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol." year="1996">Miller 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
One record has to be added for Syria: small young plants with only a few flowers and flower buds (Syria, Adra, desert, 27 Mar 1931, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">R. Gombault 1998</emphasis>
, P04583848!), previously reported as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. mesembryanthemoides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="mesembryanthemoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. mesembryanthemoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" author="Bohley, K" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="32" pageNumber="77" pagination="124 - 147" refId="B9" refString="Bohley, K, Winter, PJD, Kadereit, G, 2017. A revision of Sesuvium (Aizoaceae, Sesuvioideae). Systematic Botany 42 (1): 124 - 147, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" title="A revision of Sesuvium (Aizoaceae, Sesuvioideae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" volume="42" year="2017">Bohley et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Surprisingly, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in other regions of the world as well (re-identifications of AS): (1) North Vietnam (Tonkin, Hải 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Phòng">Phong</normalizedToken>
, sandy seashores, Jul 1908, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
Ch. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Alleizette">D'Alleizette</normalizedToken>
2723
</emphasis>
, L1693583!, a new record for Southeast Asia) and (2) Hawaii [USA], Oahu, 10 Aug 1967, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">D. Herbst 523</emphasis>
(L0717044!). Both specimens were initially identified by the collectors as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. portulacastrum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="portulacastrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. portulacastrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
Here, neophytic 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reported for the first time from Macaronesia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Distribution map of Sesuvium portulacastrum subsp. persoonii (circles) and S. verrucosum (stars)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179520" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">17</figureCitation>
), i.e. from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Vicente (Cape Verde) and Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain). In Gran Canaria, the species is well-established and dominant in a dried-out riverbed and extends to the beach and young dunes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Sesuvium verrucosum: A green-leaved plants, B red-leaved plants. Photographs by F. Verloove (Gran Canaria, Canary Islands, Spain, spring 2017)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179523" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">20</figureCitation>
). So far, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been recorded in other suitable habitats in the area (pers. obs. by Marcos Salas-Pascual in 2016 and Filip Verloove in March and April 2017) and it remains unknown how the species was introduced. Due to the evident invasive character of this species, it may be found in other African countries.
</paragraph>
